ss="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong><em>Dressmaker’s Treasury </em></strong><strong>is a collection of key tools and skills which every dressmaker needs for successful work. </strong></p><p><strong>I am offering you a great instrument to help you acquire more confidence for fulfilling your creative projects! </strong>You will no longer have any fear of complex sophisticated garments! You will learn to work with mock-ups, make crinolines of non-standard shapes, and sew various kinds of fabric cases for petticoats to enhance the fullness of the main skirt.</p><p><strong>Our main goal at the Corset Academy </strong>is to teach you how to sew wedding and evening garments. And I want you to be able to sew a high-quality garment within a relatively short time.</p><p><strong>I don’t want you to spend lots of time on doing complicated calculations and making basic skirt patterns! </strong></p><p><strong>All necessary materials are included in the course:</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in the actual size (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in half the actual size for sewing mock-ups and designing new skirt models (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculation of all parameters required for cutting a trapeze-shaped skirt, a half-circle skirt, and a full-sweep skirt (HTML). These tables contain 18 tabs for calculating necessary parameters for the mentioned types of skirts, horizontal and vertical ruffles, falbalas, and the elastic waistband skirt.</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculations with fixed parameters for the trapeze-shaped skirt, the half-circle skirt, and the full-sweep skirt (HTML);</h4></li></ul><h4>Fixed parameters (i.e. measurements) allow you to quickly calculate necessary data for cutting ruffles and falbalas for a skirt of a certain size: consumption of main fabric, lining fabric, decorative materials, etc.</h4><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Our new course&nbsp;<em>Dressmaker’s Treasury. Wedding Skirts and Petticoats </em>is a collection of important methods and skills which every dressmaker must know in order to achieve good results. It will be equally helpful for beginners and for experienced professionals! </strong></p><p><strong>Every professional dressmaker knows that sewing complex wedding skirts </strong>is not just about sewing together kilometers of fabric. The key thing is correct calculations and your ability to “foresee” the final results and related fabric consumption well before you start cutting and sewing.</p><p>I would also like to emphasize that the skirt from this course is merely a foundation for your own masterpieces. Let your creativity bloom!</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Enjoy it!</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;3h 31m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-17-half-circle-skirt-with-circular-folds/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-17-half-circle-skirt-with-circular-folds/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2018-05-04T17:18:24+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2018-05-07T18:43:25+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2018"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 17. Half-Circle Skirt with Circular Folds."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 17. Half-Circle Skirt with Circular Folds."><meta itemprop="description" content="In this tutorial, I would like to talk about half-circle skirts with deep circular folds. We will also discuss the same kind of folds in full sweep and trapeze skirts"><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding Skirts and Petticoats. Theoretical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding skirts and petticoats. theoretical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 17. Half-Circle Skirt with Circular Folds.</h1><p><strong>In this tutorial, I would like to talk about half-circle skirts with deep circular folds. We will also discuss the same kind of folds in full sweep and trapeze skirts in the tutorials to follow. </strong></p><p><strong>Such skirts are very popular today. The folds themselves can all be made in the same direction, they can also be circular folds, inverted pleats, or box pleats. </strong></p><p><strong>In order to cut a skirt like this, you need to take the fold depth (width), multiply it by the number of folds, and add it up to the Waist Circumference.</strong> You are not likely to fit into the standard fabric width if you are making deep folds.</p><p><strong>It is necessary to reinforce the folds to make them more pronounced and help them hold their shape. </strong>Depending on the fabric, this can be done by duplicating the top part of the skirt, by using soft Rigilene inserts, or by adding strips of high or medium stiffness mesh fabric cut on the bias.</p><p><strong>Folds don’t necessarily have to be even along the entire waistline. </strong>Sometimes you have to change the direction of folds as you move toward the sides from the centre. For example, folds made perpendicular to the waistline may start sticking up and refuse to settle down nicely because of the woman’s curvy hips or because of the shape of the inner construction.</p><p><strong>And again, we cannot do without a mock-up and a half-scale dress-form here. </strong></p><p><strong>Tip:</strong> you can attach the folds to the base of the skirt along their full length with thread chains in one or several spots to prevent them from getting damaged during movement. It is recommended to secure the folds by the seam allowances.</p><p><strong>First of all, let us do some preliminary calculations for our half-circle skirt with deep folds. </strong>All calculations will be done for the half-scale dress-form.</p><p><strong>We will use the following parameters: </strong></p><p>- Waist Circumference – 37cm,</p><p>- Skirt Length – 56cm,</p><p>- Fold Depth – 3cm.</p><p>If it were a skirt without folds, we would start from calculating the waist opening radius.</p><p><strong>But in our case, we need to first determine the amount of 3cm folds along the waistline. </strong></p><p><strong>This is done by dividing Waist Circumference by Fold Depth. </strong></p><p><strong>Let us take 36cm for the Waist Circumference to make it even. </strong></p><p><strong>In this case, the number of folds along the waistline will be as follows:</strong></p><p><strong>36cm / 3cm = 12</strong></p><p><strong>Now, in order to find the radius for cutting the waist opening in our half-circle skirt, </strong>we need to first multiply the Fold Depth by two (because the fold has two edges hiding beneath the outer part), multiply it by the number of folds, add it up to the Waist Circumference, and divide the resulting value by<br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image002.png" alt="">&nbsp;(and<br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image002.png" alt="">&nbsp;= 3.14).</p><p><strong>R =</strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image004.png" alt=""><strong>&nbsp; ≈ 35cm</strong></p><p><strong>The large radius R(L) for cutting the bottom edge of the skirt is found by adding the Skirt Length to the waist opening radius:</strong></p><p><strong>R(L) = 35cm + 56cm = 91cm</strong></p><p><strong>Even these preliminary values are enough to see that we are not fitting into the standard width of fabric </strong>which is 75cm in half scale. We need at least 91cm.</p><p>In this case, we will have to divide the skirt in gores or use curtain fabric of a suitable width. By the way, you can find curtain fabric of very high quality today. Wedding and evening fashion designers use it quite widely. Curtain fabric can be thick and thin and its width varies from 280cm up to 320cm.</p><p>This means you can always find curtain fabric of suitable width and quality at a rather decent price.</p><p><strong>We are not yet done with our calculations though. </strong></p><p>We need to find the length of the hem with folds closed (as if there were no folds on the skirt) <strong>to make the skirt settle in a graceful way along the bottom. </strong></p><p><strong>Hem length will help us determine the length of the bottom hoop to choose a matching petticoat. </strong></p><p><strong>The waist opening radius for our skirt with folds closed is as follows:</strong></p><p><strong>R =</strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image006.png" alt=""><strong>&nbsp;= 11.8cm ≈ 12cm</strong></p><p><strong>Consequently, the large radius R(L) of our half-circle skirt with folds closed will be: </strong></p><p><strong>R(L) = 12cm + 56cm = 68cm</strong></p><p><strong>Knowing the large radius of our skirt with folds closed, we can easily calculate its hem length which is equal to a half circumference of L: </strong></p><p><strong>L = </strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image008.png" alt=""><strong>&nbsp;х R(L) = </strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image008.png" alt=""><strong>&nbsp;х 68 = 213cm</strong></p><p><strong>Therefore, we should use a petticoat with about a 210cm long bottom hoop for our mock-up skirt with folds closed. </strong></p><p>This corresponds with 420cm in the actual size.</p><p><strong>It is quite a full petticoat. </strong>You can tell the skirt will be really full after putting it on the dress-form.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>It would be a big mistake to stop calculating and start cutting at this stage. Let me show what awaits you in this case and why. </strong></p><p><strong>First of all, let us find what depth the folds will have along the hem of the skirt if they are 3cm deep along the waistline.&nbsp; </strong></p><p>We know the large radius of the skirt with folds included: <strong>R(L) = 91cm</strong></p><p><strong>In this case, the hem length with folds included (L1) will be: </strong></p><p><strong>L1 = </strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image008.png" alt=""><strong>&nbsp;х R(L) = 3.14 х 91 = 285cm</strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Let us analyze the results. </strong>The bottom hoop of our petticoat with folds excluded (i.e. closed) is supposed to have a length of 210cm, while the hem of our skirt is 285cm long with folds included. Therefore, the difference between these two values makes up the length of the hem which falls upon the folds. It is a rather small value:</p><p><strong>285cm – 210cm = 75cm</strong></p><p><strong>Considering that there are twelve folds, here is how much fabric falls upon one fold down the bottom of the skirt:</strong></p><p><strong>75cm / 12cm = 6.25cm</strong></p><p><strong>Then, every fold will have the following width along the hem of the skirt: </strong></p><p><strong>6.25cm / 2cm ≈ 3.1cm</strong></p><p><strong>Let us sum up the results: </strong>folds with a width of 3cm at the top have the same width of 3cm down the bottom. This means we cannot expect to be able to make these folds wide down the bottom.</p><p><strong>It is clear in the drawing below that all our folds will have the same width of about 3cm along their full length. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>But we want a skirt with deep folds along the bottom edge, i.e. much wider than 3cm, so they basically take up the full length of the hem. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image018.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>We have done all calculations right. What is the problem then? </strong></p><p><strong>Let us see what petticoat we need to use to give our folds a beautiful shape down the bottom. </strong></p><p><strong>The hem length with folds included (L1) is 285cm. </strong>We have twelve folds and we want them to cover the entire bottom edge of the skirt.</p><p><strong>We can then find the length of hem per fold: </strong></p><p><strong>285cm / 12 ≈ 24cm</strong></p><p><strong>Every fold is made of three equal parts: one face part and two inner parts hiding underneath it. </strong></p><p><strong>And this means every fold has the following width down the bottom: </strong></p><p><strong>24cm / 3 = 8cm</strong></p><p><strong>This is the width we want to achieve. </strong></p><p>We want to make deep beautiful folds along the hem of the skirt. These folds are supposed to resemble triangles, narrower at the top and wider at the bottom. Folds that are 3cm wide at the top, i.e. along the waistline, and 8cm wide down the bottom, i.e. along the hem, make quite nice triangles. If we take our skirt in the actual size, the difference between the top and the bottom width of folds, i.e. between 6cm and 16cm, will be 10cm. It is exactly what we want.</p><p><strong>And now let us calculate the length of the hem made of twelve 8cm wide folds with the folds closed:</strong></p><p><strong>8cm х 12 = 96cm</strong></p><p><strong>Only the smallest possible petticoat with a 100cm long bottom hoop would suit folds like these. But you can barely walk in it. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image020.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>The main conclusion we can make is that the half-circle skirt does not provide enough volume for making large deep folds down the bottom. </strong></p><p><strong>A skirt like this can only be cut as a half-circle skirt if there are shallow folds down the bottom and if they are not going along the full length of the hem, which is what you see in the picture below. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image022.jpg" alt=""></p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation Tables of All Parameters Required:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sun/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/halfSun/index.htm" target="_blank">Half-Circle Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/dlina/index.htm" target="_blank">Full-Sweep Skirt</a> </strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation&nbsp;Tables with Fixed Parameters:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sunFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/halfSunFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Half-Circle Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/dlinaFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Full-Sweep Skirt</a></strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Sewing patterns are in PDF format.</p><p>To print sewing patterns open the files, press “print” and choose “<strong>PRINT IN ACTUAL SIZE</strong>“.</p><p>In each&nbsp;file the pattern is divided &nbsp;to A4 paper sheets for home printer.</p><h3>Skirt Patterns:</h3><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Patterns/flaredSkirt.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/them